1
00:00:13,46 --> 00:00:15,635000000000002
Chris Anderson: This is sucha strange thing.

2
00:00:15,659 --> 00:00:18,817
Your software, Linux,is in millions of computers,

3
00:00:18,841 --> 00:00:22,388
it probably powers much of the Internet.

4
00:00:22,412 --> 00:00:24,174999999999997
And I think that there are, like,

5
00:00:24,199 --> 00:00:27,544
a billion and a half activeAndroid devices out there.

6
00:00:27,568 --> 00:00:30,169
Your software is in everysingle one of them.

7
00:00:30,808 --> 00:00:31,958
It&amp;#39;s kind of amazing.

8
00:00:31,982 --> 00:00:37,016999999999996
You must have some amazingsoftware headquarters driving all this.

9
00:00:37,041 --> 00:00:40,346999999999994
That&amp;#39;s what I thought -- and I was shockedwhen I saw a picture of it.

10
00:00:40,371 --> 00:00:41,571000000000005
I mean, this is --

11
00:00:41,595 --> 00:00:43,845
this is the Linux world headquarters.

12
00:00:43,869 --> 00:00:45,859
(Laughter)

13
00:00:45,883 --> 00:00:49,889
(Applause)

14
00:00:49,913 --> 00:00:52,199
Linus Torvalds: It reallydoesn&amp;#39;t look like much.

15
00:00:52,223 --> 00:00:53,899
And I have to say,

16
00:00:53,923 --> 00:00:57,743
the most interesting part in this picture,

17
00:00:57,767 --> 00:00:59,470000000000006
that people mostly react to,

18
00:00:59,494 --> 00:01:00,937
is the walking desk.

19
00:01:00,961 --> 00:01:03,66
It is the most interestingpart in my office

20
00:01:03,684 --> 00:01:05,64399999999999
and I&amp;#39;m not actually using it anymore.

21
00:01:05,668 --> 00:01:07,96000000000001
And I think the two things are related.

22
00:01:09,206 --> 00:01:11,531
The way I work is ...

23
00:01:13,245 --> 00:01:17,59400000000001
I want to not have external stimulation.

24
00:01:18,17 --> 00:01:23,437
You can kind of see,on the walls are this light green.

25
00:01:23,461 --> 00:01:27,925
I&amp;#39;m told that at mental institutionsthey use that on the walls.

26
00:01:27,949 --> 00:01:28,996
(Laughter)

27
00:01:29,02 --> 00:01:30,80499999999999
It&amp;#39;s like a calming color,

28
00:01:30,829 --> 00:01:33,946
it&amp;#39;s not somethingthat really stimulates you.

29
00:01:35,064 --> 00:01:39,48899999999999
What you can&amp;#39;t see is the computer here,you only see the screen,

30
00:01:39,513 --> 00:01:42,894
but the main thing I worryabout in my computer is --

31
00:01:42,918 --> 00:01:46,253
it doesn&amp;#39;t have to be bigand powerful, although I like that --

32
00:01:46,277 --> 00:01:49,109
it really has to be completely silent.

33
00:01:49,975 --> 00:01:51,98599999999999
I know people who work for Google

34
00:01:52,01 --> 00:01:55,217
and they have their ownsmall data center at home,

35
00:01:55,241 --> 00:01:56,393
and I don&amp;#39;t do that.

36
00:01:56,417 --> 00:02:00,122
My office is the mostboring office you&amp;#39;ll ever see.

37
00:02:00,146 --> 00:02:03,66
And I sit there alone in the quiet.

38
00:02:04,136 --> 00:02:06,173
If the cat comes up,

39
00:02:06,197 --> 00:02:08,034
it sits in my lap.

40
00:02:08,058 --> 00:02:10,248
And I want to hear the cat purring,

41
00:02:10,272 --> 00:02:13,446
not the sound of the fans in the computer.

42
00:02:13,47 --> 00:02:14,779
CA: So this is astonishing,

43
00:02:14,803 --> 00:02:17,481
because working this way,

44
00:02:17,505 --> 00:02:20,493
you&amp;#39;re able to run this vasttechnology empire --

45
00:02:20,517 --> 00:02:21,738
it is an empire --

46
00:02:21,762 --> 00:02:25,462
so that&amp;#39;s an amazing testamentto the power of open source.

47
00:02:25,486 --> 00:02:29,66199999999998
Tell us how you gotto understand open source

48
00:02:29,686 --> 00:02:31,93800000000002
and how it leadto the development of Linux.

49
00:02:33,546 --> 00:02:35,051
LT: I mean, I still work alone.

50
00:02:35,075 --> 00:02:38,642
Really -- I work alone in my house,

51
00:02:38,666 --> 00:02:40,05599999999998
ofte in my bathrobe.

52
00:02:40,08 --> 00:02:42,64100000000002
When a photographer shows up, I dress up,

53
00:02:42,665 --> 00:02:43,951
so I have clothes on.

54
00:02:43,975 --> 00:02:45,212
(Laughter)

55
00:02:45,236 --> 00:02:47,308
And that&amp;#39;s how I&amp;#39;ve always worked.

56
00:02:47,332 --> 00:02:49,34
I mean, this was how I started Linux, too.

57
00:02:49,364 --> 00:02:53,013
I did not start Linuxas a collaborative project.

58
00:02:53,037 --> 00:02:57,91500000000002
I started it as onein a series of many projects

59
00:02:57,939 --> 00:03:01,896
I had done at the time for myself,

60
00:03:01,92 --> 00:03:03,82199999999997
partly because I needed the end result,

61
00:03:03,846 --> 00:03:06,148
but even more because I justenjoyed programming.

62
00:03:06,172 --> 00:03:10,546
So it was about the end of the journey,

63
00:03:10,57 --> 00:03:13,916
which, 25 years later,we still have not reached.

64
00:03:13,94 --> 00:03:17,657
But it was really about the factthat I was looking for a project on my own

65
00:03:17,681 --> 00:03:21,51000000000002
and there was no open source,really, on my radar at all.

66
00:03:21,988 --> 00:03:24,0
And what happened is ...

67
00:03:24,668 --> 00:03:29,22
the project grows and becomes somethingyou want to show off to people.

68
00:03:30,552 --> 00:03:34,66899999999998
Really, this is more of a, &amp;quot;Wow,look at what I did!&amp;quot;

69
00:03:34,693 --> 00:03:37,24800000000002
And trust me -- it was notthat great back then.

70
00:03:38,128 --> 00:03:40,00199999999998
I made it publicly available,

71
00:03:40,026 --> 00:03:42,132
and it wasn&amp;#39;t evenopen source at that point.

72
00:03:42,156 --> 00:03:47,32500000000002
At that point it was source that was open,but there was no intention

73
00:03:47,349 --> 00:03:52,463
behind using the kind of open-sourcemethodology that we think of today

74
00:03:52,487 --> 00:03:53,638
to improve it.

75
00:03:53,662 --> 00:03:54,81300000000002
It was more like,

76
00:03:54,837 --> 00:03:57,774
&amp;quot;Look, I&amp;#39;ve been workingon this for half a year,

77
00:03:58,459 --> 00:04:00,198
I&amp;#39;d love to have comments.&amp;quot;

78
00:04:03,217 --> 00:04:04,869
At the University of Helsinki,

79
00:04:04,893 --> 00:04:08,608
I had a friend who was oneof the open source --

80
00:04:08,632 --> 00:04:12,288
it was called mainly&amp;quot;free software&amp;quot; back then --

81
00:04:12,312 --> 00:04:16,586
and he actually introduced meto the notion that, hey,

82
00:04:16,61 --> 00:04:21,96700000000004
you can use these open-sourcelicenses that had been around.

83
00:04:24,114 --> 00:04:26,155
And I thought about it for a while.

84
00:04:26,179 --> 00:04:29,66999999999996
I was actually worried about the wholecommercial interests coming in.

85
00:04:29,694 --> 00:04:34,168
I mean, that&amp;#39;s one of the worriesI think most people who start out have,

86
00:04:34,192 --> 00:04:39,152
is that they worry about somebodytaking advantage of their work, right?

87
00:04:39,603 --> 00:04:42,859
And I decided, &amp;quot;What the hell?&amp;quot;

88
00:04:43,74 --> 00:04:44,89
And --

89
00:04:44,914 --> 00:04:46,209
CA: And then at some point,

90
00:04:46,233 --> 00:04:48,693
someone contributedsome code that you thought,

91
00:04:48,717 --> 00:04:51,888
&amp;quot;Wow, that really is interesting,I would not have thought of that.

92
00:04:51,912 --> 00:04:53,563
This could actually improve this.&amp;quot;

93
00:04:53,587 --> 00:04:56,11199999999997
LT: It didn&amp;#39;t even startby people contributing code,

94
00:04:56,136 --> 00:04:59,115
it was more that peoplestarted contributing ideas.

95
00:04:59,748 --> 00:05:02,99399999999997
And just the fact that somebody elsetakes a look at your project --

96
00:05:03,018 --> 00:05:05,566
and I&amp;#39;m sure it&amp;#39;s trueof other things, too,

97
00:05:05,59 --> 00:05:07,42699999999996
but it&amp;#39;s definitely true in code --

98
00:05:07,451 --> 00:05:10,95000000000005
is that somebody elsetakes an interest in your code,

99
00:05:10,974 --> 00:05:13,496
looks at it enough to actuallygive you feedback

100
00:05:13,52 --> 00:05:15,409
and give you ideas.

101
00:05:15,433 --> 00:05:17,134
That was a huge thing for me.

102
00:05:17,158 --> 00:05:20,35
I was 21 at the time, so I was young,

103
00:05:20,374 --> 00:05:23,61100000000005
but I had already programmedfor half my life, basically.

104
00:05:24,372 --> 00:05:28,344
And every project before thathad been completely personal

105
00:05:28,368 --> 00:05:31,475
and it was a revelation when peoplejust started commenting,

106
00:05:31,499 --> 00:05:34,8
started giving feedback on your code.

107
00:05:34,824 --> 00:05:38,596
And even before they startedgiving code back,

108
00:05:38,62 --> 00:05:41,361
that was, I think, one of the bigmoments where I said,

109
00:05:41,385 --> 00:05:43,258
&amp;quot;I love other people!&amp;quot;

110
00:05:43,282 --> 00:05:44,43899999999996
Don&amp;#39;t get me wrong --

111
00:05:44,463 --> 00:05:46,08700000000005
I&amp;#39;m actually not a people person.

112
00:05:46,111 --> 00:05:49,476
(Laughter)

113
00:05:49,5 --> 00:05:52,052
I don&amp;#39;t really love other people --

114
00:05:52,076 --> 00:05:53,096
(Laughter)

115
00:05:53,12 --> 00:05:54,746
But I love computers,

116
00:05:54,77 --> 00:05:56,98499999999996
I love interacting with otherpeople on email,

117
00:05:57,009 --> 00:06:00,341
because it kind of gives you that buffer.

118
00:06:00,365 --> 00:06:06,866
But I do love other people who commentand get involved in my project.

119
00:06:06,89 --> 00:06:08,543
And it made it so much more.

120
00:06:09,273 --> 00:06:12,107
CA: So was there a momentwhen you saw what was being built

121
00:06:12,131 --> 00:06:14,33799999999997
and it suddenly started taking off,

122
00:06:14,362 --> 00:06:17,65200000000004
and you thought, &amp;quot;Wait a sec,this actually could be something huge,

123
00:06:17,676 --> 00:06:20,58799999999997
not just a personal projectthat I&amp;#39;m getting nice feedback on,

124
00:06:20,612 --> 00:06:24,932
but a kind of explosive developmentin the whole technology world&amp;quot;?

125
00:06:25,821 --> 00:06:26,98
LT: Not really.

126
00:06:27,004 --> 00:06:30,576
I mean, the big point for me, really,was not when it was becoming huge,

127
00:06:30,6 --> 00:06:32,73400000000004
it was when it was becoming little.

128
00:06:33,709 --> 00:06:37,226
The big point for me was not being alone

129
00:06:37,25 --> 00:06:40,967
and having 10, maybe 100people being involved --

130
00:06:40,991 --> 00:06:42,46999999999997
that was a big point.

131
00:06:42,494 --> 00:06:45,533
Then everything else was very gradual.

132
00:06:45,557 --> 00:06:49,81600000000003
Going from 100 people to a million peopleis not a big deal -- to me.

133
00:06:49,84 --> 00:06:51,673
Well, I mean, maybe it is if you&amp;#39;re --

134
00:06:51,697 --> 00:06:52,698
(Laughter)

135
00:06:52,722 --> 00:06:55,44
If you want to sell your resultthen it&amp;#39;s a huge deal --

136
00:06:55,464 --> 00:06:56,615
don&amp;#39;t get me wrong.

137
00:06:56,639 --> 00:06:58,766
But if you&amp;#39;re interested in the technology

138
00:06:58,79 --> 00:07:00,64500000000004
and you&amp;#39;re interested in the project,

139
00:07:00,669 --> 00:07:02,54999999999995
the big part was getting the community.

140
00:07:02,574 --> 00:07:04,19800000000004
Then the community grew gradually.

141
00:07:04,222 --> 00:07:07,57
And there&amp;#39;s actually nota single point where I went like,

142
00:07:08,166 --> 00:07:10,342
&amp;quot;Wow, that just took off!&amp;quot; because it --

143
00:07:10,366 --> 00:07:13,69
I mean -- it took a long time, relatively.

144
00:07:13,714 --> 00:07:16,69
CA: So all the technologiststhat I talk to really credit you

145
00:07:16,714 --> 00:07:19,588
with massively changing their work.

146
00:07:19,612 --> 00:07:21,235
And it&amp;#39;s not just Linux,

147
00:07:21,259 --> 00:07:22,70500000000004
it&amp;#39;s this thing called Git,

148
00:07:22,729 --> 00:07:26,741
which is this management systemfor software development.

149
00:07:26,765 --> 00:07:29,55
Tell us briefly about thatand your role in that.

150
00:07:30,481 --> 00:07:32,27
LT: So one of the issues we had,

151
00:07:32,294 --> 00:07:35,346
and this took a while to start to appear,

152
00:07:35,37 --> 00:07:36,525
is when you ...

153
00:07:37,708 --> 00:07:43,04
When you grow from having 10 peopleor 100 people working on a project

154
00:07:43,064 --> 00:07:45,452
to having 10,000 people, which --

155
00:07:45,476 --> 00:07:48,942
I mean, right now we&amp;#39;re in the situationwhere just on the kernel,

156
00:07:48,966 --> 00:07:52,14
we have 1,000 people involvedin every single release

157
00:07:52,164 --> 00:07:55,75
and that&amp;#39;s every two months,roughly two or three months.

158
00:07:56,336 --> 00:07:58,757
Some of those people don&amp;#39;t do a lot.

159
00:07:58,781 --> 00:08:01,36400000000003
There&amp;#39;s a lot of peoplewho make small, small changes.

160
00:08:01,388 --> 00:08:03,63399999999996
But to maintain this,

161
00:08:03,658 --> 00:08:06,547
the scale changes howyou have to maintain it.

162
00:08:06,571 --> 00:08:08,96900000000005
And we went through a lot of pain.

163
00:08:10,713 --> 00:08:17,242
And there are whole projectsthat do only source-code maintenance.

164
00:08:17,266 --> 00:08:20,558
CVS is the one that used to bethe most commonly used,

165
00:08:20,582 --> 00:08:24,479
and I hated CVS with a passionand refused to touch it

166
00:08:24,503 --> 00:08:27,566
and tried something elsethat was radical and interesting

167
00:08:27,59 --> 00:08:30,246
and everybody else hated.

168
00:08:31,004 --> 00:08:32,378
CA: (Laughs)

169
00:08:32,402 --> 00:08:34,49
LT: And we were in this bad spot,

170
00:08:34,514 --> 00:08:37,331
where we had thousands of peoplewho wanted to participate,

171
00:08:37,355 --> 00:08:42,3960000000001
but in many ways,I was the kind of break point,

172
00:08:42,42 --> 00:08:44,944
where I could not scale to the point

173
00:08:44,968 --> 00:08:47,7679999999999
where I could workwith thousands of people.

174
00:08:47,792 --> 00:08:50,244
So Git is my second big project,

175
00:08:50,268 --> 00:08:54,806
which was only created for meto maintain my first big project.

176
00:08:55,433 --> 00:08:57,68
And this is literally how I work.

177
00:08:57,704 --> 00:09:00,209
I don&amp;#39;t code for --

178
00:09:00,233 --> 00:09:01,9549999999999
well, I do code for fun --

179
00:09:01,979 --> 00:09:04,36
but I want to codefor something meaningful

180
00:09:04,384 --> 00:09:08,431
so every single project I&amp;#39;ve ever donehas been something I needed

181
00:09:08,455 --> 00:09:09,831
and --

182
00:09:09,855 --> 00:09:13,288
CA: So really, both Linuxand Git kind of arose

183
00:09:13,312 --> 00:09:15,648
almost as an unintended consequence

184
00:09:15,672 --> 00:09:18,3430000000001
of your desire not to haveto work with too many people.

185
00:09:18,367 --> 00:09:19,5179999999999
LT: Absolutely. Yes.

186
00:09:19,542 --> 00:09:20,6220000000001
(Laughter)

187
00:09:20,646 --> 00:09:22,2959999999999
CA: That&amp;#39;s amazing.LT: Yeah.

188
00:09:22,32 --> 00:09:23,812
(Applause)

189
00:09:23,836 --> 00:09:27,227
And yet, you&amp;#39;re the manwho&amp;#39;s transformed technology

190
00:09:27,251 --> 00:09:28,568
not just once but twice,

191
00:09:28,592 --> 00:09:31,175
and we have to tryand understand why it is.

192
00:09:31,199 --> 00:09:32,8829999999999
You&amp;#39;ve given us some clues, but ...

193
00:09:32,907 --> 00:09:37,548
Here&amp;#39;s a picture of you as a kid,with a Rubik&amp;#39;s Cube.

194
00:09:37,572 --> 00:09:41,692
You mentioned that you&amp;#39;ve beenprogramming since you were like 10 or 11,

195
00:09:41,716 --> 00:09:43,081
half your life.

196
00:09:43,105 --> 00:09:46,921
Were you this sort of computergenius, you know, übernerd,

197
00:09:46,945 --> 00:09:49,4300000000001
were you the star at schoolwho could do everything?

198
00:09:49,454 --> 00:09:50,986
What were you like as a kid?

199
00:09:52,13 --> 00:09:54,623
LT: Yeah, I think I wasthe prototypical nerd.

200
00:09:54,647 --> 00:09:55,916
I mean, I was ...

201
00:09:57,13 --> 00:09:59,092
I was not a people person back then.

202
00:09:59,116 --> 00:10:01,696
That&amp;#39;s my younger brother.

203
00:10:01,72 --> 00:10:04,5070000000001
I was clearly more interestedin the Rubik&amp;#39;s Cube

204
00:10:04,531 --> 00:10:06,0559999999999
than my younger brother.

205
00:10:06,08 --> 00:10:07,167
(Laughter)

206
00:10:07,191 --> 00:10:10,311
My younger sister,who&amp;#39;s not in the picture,

207
00:10:10,335 --> 00:10:12,749
when we had family meetings --

208
00:10:12,773 --> 00:10:16,565
and it&amp;#39;s not a huge family, but I have,like, a couple of cousins --

209
00:10:16,589 --> 00:10:19,4530000000001
she would prep me beforehand.

210
00:10:19,477 --> 00:10:22,043
Like, before I steppedinto the room she would say,

211
00:10:22,067 --> 00:10:24,61
&amp;quot;OK. That&amp;#39;s so-and-so ...&amp;quot;

212
00:10:25,925 --> 00:10:28,2539999999999
Because I was not --

213
00:10:28,278 --> 00:10:29,493
I was a geek.

214
00:10:29,517 --> 00:10:30,6830000000001
I was into computers,

215
00:10:30,707 --> 00:10:31,866
I was into math,

216
00:10:31,89 --> 00:10:33,0409999999999
I was into physics.

217
00:10:33,065 --> 00:10:34,216
I was good at that.

218
00:10:34,24 --> 00:10:37,026
I don&amp;#39;t think I wasparticularly exceptional.

219
00:10:37,554 --> 00:10:39,9449999999999
Apparently, my sister said

220
00:10:39,969 --> 00:10:46,82
that my biggest exceptional qualitywas that I would not let go.

221
00:10:47,618 --> 00:10:50,1750000000001
CA: OK, so let&amp;#39;s go there,because that&amp;#39;s interesting.

222
00:10:50,199 --> 00:10:51,3729999999999
You would not let go.

223
00:10:51,397 --> 00:10:54,2620000000001
So that&amp;#39;s not about beinga geek and being smart,

224
00:10:54,286 --> 00:10:57,391
that&amp;#39;s about being ... stubborn?

225
00:10:57,415 --> 00:10:58,942
LT: That&amp;#39;s about being stubborn.

226
00:10:58,966 --> 00:11:00,354
That&amp;#39;s about, like,

227
00:11:01,093 --> 00:11:03,293
just starting something

228
00:11:03,317 --> 00:11:08,767
and not saying, &amp;quot;OK, I&amp;#39;m done,let&amp;#39;s do something else --

229
00:11:08,791 --> 00:11:09,9780000000001
Look: shiny!&amp;quot;

230
00:11:10,954 --> 00:11:14,3349999999999
And I notice that in manyother parts in my life, too.

231
00:11:15,47 --> 00:11:18,72
I lived in Silicon Valley for seven years.

232
00:11:18,744 --> 00:11:22,856
And I worked for the samecompany, in Silicon Valley,

233
00:11:22,88 --> 00:11:24,594
for the whole time.

234
00:11:24,618 --> 00:11:26,1560000000001
That is unheard of.

235
00:11:27,204 --> 00:11:28,971
That&amp;#39;s not how Silicon Valley works.

236
00:11:28,995 --> 00:11:32,574
The whole point of Silicon Valleyis that people jump between jobs

237
00:11:32,598 --> 00:11:35,2249999999999
to kind of mix up the pot.

238
00:11:35,249 --> 00:11:37,129
And that&amp;#39;s not the kind of person I am.

