293
00:14:12,526 --> 00:14:13,6769999999999
(Laughter)

294
00:14:13,701 --> 00:14:15,84
So there&amp;#39;s different kinds of people,

295
00:14:15,864 --> 00:14:18,729
and I&amp;#39;m not making excuses,I&amp;#39;m trying to explain.

296
00:14:18,753 --> 00:14:20,4190000000001
CA: Now, when we talked last week,

297
00:14:20,443 --> 00:14:22,928
you talked about someother trait that you have,

298
00:14:22,952 --> 00:14:24,543
which I found really interesting.

299
00:14:24,567 --> 00:14:25,95
It&amp;#39;s this idea called taste.

300
00:14:25,974 --> 00:14:27,976
And I&amp;#39;ve just got a couple of images here.

301
00:14:28,354 --> 00:14:32,3570000000001
I think this is an example of notparticularly good taste in code,

302
00:14:32,381 --> 00:14:35,372
and this one is better taste,

303
00:14:35,396 --> 00:14:37,459
which one can immediately see.

304
00:14:37,483 --> 00:14:39,4559999999999
What is the difference between these two?

305
00:14:40,639 --> 00:14:41,821
LT: So this is --

306
00:14:41,845 --> 00:14:44,522
How many people here actually have coded?

307
00:14:45,671 --> 00:14:47,191
CA: Oh my goodness.

308
00:14:47,215 --> 00:14:48,37
LT: So I guarantee you,

309
00:14:48,394 --> 00:14:49,939
everybody who raised their hand,

310
00:14:49,963 --> 00:14:52,584
they have done what&amp;#39;s calleda singly-linked list.

311
00:14:52,608 --> 00:14:54,617
And it&amp;#39;s taught --

312
00:14:55,115 --> 00:14:58,706
This, the first not verygood taste approach,

313
00:14:58,73 --> 00:15:02,797
is basically how it&amp;#39;s taught to be donewhen you start out coding.

314
00:15:02,821 --> 00:15:04,865
And you don&amp;#39;t have to understand the code.

315
00:15:04,889 --> 00:15:06,945
The most interesting part to me

316
00:15:06,969 --> 00:15:09,158
is the last if statement.

317
00:15:10,933 --> 00:15:13,193
Because what happensin a singly-linked list --

318
00:15:13,217 --> 00:15:16,867
this is trying to removean existing entry from a list --

319
00:15:16,891 --> 00:15:20,733
and there&amp;#39;s a differencebetween if it&amp;#39;s the first entry

320
00:15:20,757 --> 00:15:22,756
or whether it&amp;#39;s an entry in the middle.

321
00:15:22,78 --> 00:15:24,385
Because if it&amp;#39;s the first entry,

322
00:15:24,409 --> 00:15:27,425
you have to changethe pointer to the first entry.

323
00:15:27,449 --> 00:15:28,6469999999999
If it&amp;#39;s in the middle,

324
00:15:28,671 --> 00:15:31,0920000000001
you have to change the pointerof a previous entry.

325
00:15:31,116 --> 00:15:33,14
So they&amp;#39;re two completely different cases.

326
00:15:33,164 --> 00:15:34,316
CA: And that&amp;#39;s better.

327
00:15:34,34 --> 00:15:35,5210000000001
LT: And this is better.

328
00:15:35,94 --> 00:15:38,263
It does not have the if statement.

329
00:15:38,637 --> 00:15:40,8499999999999
And it doesn&amp;#39;t really matter --

330
00:15:40,874 --> 00:15:44,075
I don&amp;#39;t want you understandwhy it doesn&amp;#39;t have the if statement,

331
00:15:44,099 --> 00:15:45,441
but I want you to understand

332
00:15:45,465 --> 00:15:48,09
that sometimes you can seea problem in a different way

333
00:15:48,114 --> 00:15:51,4680000000001
and rewrite it so thata special case goes away

334
00:15:51,492 --> 00:15:53,3689999999999
and becomes the normal case.

335
00:15:53,393 --> 00:15:54,932
And that&amp;#39;s good code.

336
00:15:55,328 --> 00:15:56,8779999999999
But this is simple code.

337
00:15:56,902 --> 00:15:58,2510000000001
This is CS 101.

338
00:15:58,275 --> 00:16:01,131
This is not important --although, details are important.

339
00:16:01,798 --> 00:16:05,876
To me, the sign of peopleI really want to work with

340
00:16:05,9 --> 00:16:08,573
is that they have good taste,which is how ...

341
00:16:09,295 --> 00:16:10,8919999999999
I sent you this stupid example

342
00:16:10,916 --> 00:16:13,2600000000001
that is not relevantbecause it&amp;#39;s too small.

343
00:16:13,743 --> 00:16:15,8850000000001
Good taste is much bigger than this.

344
00:16:15,909 --> 00:16:19,93
Good taste is about reallyseeing the big patterns

345
00:16:19,954 --> 00:16:24,4119999999999
and kind of instinctively knowingwhat&amp;#39;s the right way to do things.

346
00:16:24,436 --> 00:16:27,0930000000001
CA: OK, so we&amp;#39;re puttingthe pieces together here now.

347
00:16:27,736 --> 00:16:29,203
You have taste,

348
00:16:30,057 --> 00:16:32,394
in a way that&amp;#39;s meaningfulto software people.

349
00:16:32,418 --> 00:16:33,569
You&amp;#39;re --

350
00:16:33,593 --> 00:16:35,409
(Laughter)

351
00:16:35,433 --> 00:16:37,994
LT: I think it was meaningfulto some people here.

352
00:16:39,967 --> 00:16:42,884
CA: You&amp;#39;re a very smart computer coder,

353
00:16:42,908 --> 00:16:44,605
and you&amp;#39;re hellish stubborn.

354
00:16:45,622 --> 00:16:47,208
But there must be something else.

355
00:16:47,232 --> 00:16:48,855
I mean, you&amp;#39;ve changed the future.

356
00:16:48,879 --> 00:16:51,842
You must have the abilityof these grand visions of the future.

357
00:16:51,866 --> 00:16:53,127
You&amp;#39;re a visionary, right?

358
00:16:53,151 --> 00:16:55,742
LT: I&amp;#39;ve actually felt slightlyuncomfortable at TED

359
00:16:55,766 --> 00:16:57,9259999999999
for the last two days,

360
00:16:57,95 --> 00:17:00,5450000000001
because there&amp;#39;s a lotof vision going on, right?

361
00:17:00,569 --> 00:17:02,266
And I am not a visionary.

362
00:17:02,29 --> 00:17:04,519
I do not have a five-year plan.

363
00:17:04,543 --> 00:17:05,9009999999998
I&amp;#39;m an engineer.

364
00:17:05,925 --> 00:17:07,185
And I think it&amp;#39;s really --

365
00:17:07,209 --> 00:17:09,528
I mean -- I&amp;#39;m perfectlyhappy with all the people

366
00:17:09,552 --> 00:17:12,3029999999999
who are walking aroundand just staring at the clouds

367
00:17:12,327 --> 00:17:15,178
and looking at the starsand saying, &amp;quot;I want to go there.&amp;quot;

368
00:17:15,202 --> 00:17:16,654
But I&amp;#39;m looking at the ground,

