00:17:16,678 --> 00:17:19,5330000000001
and I want to fix the potholethat&amp;#39;s right in front of me

370
00:17:19,557 --> 00:17:20,917
before I fall in.

371
00:17:20,941 --> 00:17:22,56
This is the kind of person I am.

372
00:17:22,584 --> 00:17:23,6950000000002
(Cheers)

373
00:17:23,719 --> 00:17:25,031
(Applause)

374
00:17:25,055 --> 00:17:28,6660000000002
CA: So you spoke to me last weekabout these two guys.

375
00:17:29,358 --> 00:17:31,793
Who are they and howdo you relate to them?

376
00:17:32,239 --> 00:17:35,8410000000001
LT: Well, so this is kindof cliché in technology,

377
00:17:35,865 --> 00:17:37,872
the whole Tesla versus Edison,

378
00:17:37,896 --> 00:17:42,837
where Tesla is seen as the visionaryscientist and crazy idea man.

379
00:17:42,861 --> 00:17:45,643
And people love Tesla.

380
00:17:45,667 --> 00:17:48,654
I mean, there are people who nametheir companies after him.

381
00:17:48,678 --> 00:17:49,8280000000002
(Laughter)

382
00:17:51,365 --> 00:17:53,977
The other person there is Edison,

383
00:17:54,001 --> 00:17:57,508
who is actually often vilifiedfor being kind of pedestrian

384
00:17:57,532 --> 00:17:59,453
and is --

385
00:17:59,477 --> 00:18:02,199
I mean, his most famous quote is,

386
00:18:02,223 --> 00:18:06,937
&amp;quot;Genius is one percent inspirationand 99 percent perspiration.&amp;quot;

387
00:18:07,394 --> 00:18:08,847
And I&amp;#39;m in the Edison camp,

388
00:18:08,871 --> 00:18:11,055
even if people don&amp;#39;t always like him.

389
00:18:11,079 --> 00:18:14,098
Because if you actually compare the two,

390
00:18:14,122 --> 00:18:18,655
Tesla has kind of this mindgrab these days,

391
00:18:18,679 --> 00:18:20,678
but who actually changed the world?

392
00:18:21,853 --> 00:18:25,2350000000001
Edison may not have been a nice person,

393
00:18:25,259 --> 00:18:28,391
he did a lot of things --

394
00:18:28,415 --> 00:18:30,844
he was maybe not so intellectual,

395
00:18:30,868 --> 00:18:33,095
not so visionary.

396
00:18:33,119 --> 00:18:36,78
But I think I&amp;#39;m moreof an Edison than a Tesla.

397
00:18:37,669 --> 00:18:40,1070000000002
CA: So our theme at TEDthis week is dreams --

398
00:18:40,131 --> 00:18:41,478
big, bold, audacious dreams.

399
00:18:41,502 --> 00:18:43,3039999999999
You&amp;#39;re really the antidote to that.

400
00:18:43,328 --> 00:18:45,437
LT: I&amp;#39;m trying to dial it down a bit, yes.

401
00:18:45,461 --> 00:18:46,612
CA: That&amp;#39;s good.

402
00:18:46,636 --> 00:18:47,716
(Laughter)

403
00:18:47,74 --> 00:18:49,345
We embrace you, we embrace you.

404
00:18:51,046 --> 00:18:53,795
Companies like Google and manyothers have made, arguably,

405
00:18:53,819 --> 00:18:56,0249999999999
like, billions of dollarsout of your software.

406
00:18:56,049 --> 00:18:57,2
Does that piss you off?

407
00:18:57,224 --> 00:18:58,375
LT: No.

408
00:18:58,399 --> 00:19:01,033
No, it doesn&amp;#39;t piss me offfor several reasons.

409
00:19:01,057 --> 00:19:03,067
And one of them is, I&amp;#39;m doing fine.

410
00:19:03,091 --> 00:19:04,387
I&amp;#39;m really doing fine.

411
00:19:04,942 --> 00:19:06,526
But the other reason is --

412
00:19:06,55 --> 00:19:11,877
I mean, without doing the wholeopen source and really letting go thing,

413
00:19:11,901 --> 00:19:14,1270000000002
Linux would never have been what it is.

414
00:19:14,151 --> 00:19:19,247
And it&amp;#39;s brought experiencesI don&amp;#39;t really enjoy, public talking,

415
00:19:19,271 --> 00:19:21,422
but at the same time,this is an experience.

416
00:19:21,446 --> 00:19:22,7259999999999
Trust me.

417
00:19:23,238 --> 00:19:28,381
So there&amp;#39;s a lot of things going onthat make me a very happy man

418
00:19:28,405 --> 00:19:30,934
and thinking I did the right choices.

419
00:19:30,958 --> 00:19:32,8700000000001
CA: Is the open source idea --

420
00:19:32,894 --> 00:19:34,53
this is, I think we&amp;#39;ll end here --

421
00:19:34,554 --> 00:19:38,6080000000002
is the open source ideafully realized now in the world,

422
00:19:38,632 --> 00:19:41,65
or is there more that it could go,

423
00:19:41,674 --> 00:19:43,689
are there more things that it could do?

424
00:19:44,738 --> 00:19:46,972
LT: So, I&amp;#39;m of two minds there.

425
00:19:46,996 --> 00:19:51,4820000000002
I think one reason open sourceworks so well in code

426
00:19:51,506 --> 00:19:53,9150000000002
is that at the end of the day,

427
00:19:53,939 --> 00:19:57,1850000000002
code tends to be somewhat black and white.

428
00:19:57,209 --> 00:20:01,366
There&amp;#39;s often a fairly good way to decide,

429
00:20:01,39 --> 00:20:05,336
this is done correctlyand this is not done well.

430
00:20:05,36 --> 00:20:07,7379999999998
Code either works or it doesn&amp;#39;t,

431
00:20:07,762 --> 00:20:12,37
which means that there&amp;#39;s lessroom for arguments.

432
00:20:12,394 --> 00:20:16,025
And we have arguments despite this, right?

433
00:20:16,049 --> 00:20:17,964
In many other areas --

434
00:20:17,988 --> 00:20:21,729
I mean, people have talked aboutopen politics and things like that --

435
00:20:21,753 --> 00:20:24,702
and it&amp;#39;s really hard sometimes to say

436
00:20:24,726 --> 00:20:28,4830000000002
that, yes, you can apply the sameprinciples in some other areas

437
00:20:28,507 --> 00:20:33,9460000000001
just because the black and whiteturns into not just gray,

438
00:20:33,97 --> 00:20:35,573
but different colors.

439
00:20:36,339 --> 00:20:40,705
So, obviously open source in scienceis making a comeback.

440
00:20:40,729 --> 00:20:42,363
Science was there first.

441
00:20:42,387 --> 00:20:45,0539999999999
But then science ended upbeing pretty closed,

442
00:20:45,078 --> 00:20:48,702
with very expensive journalsand some of that going on.

443
00:20:48,726 --> 00:20:52,5620000000001
And open source is makinga comeback in science,

444
00:20:52,586 --> 00:20:56,733
with things like arXiv and open journals.

445
00:20:59,262 --> 00:21:01,215
Wikipedia changed the world, too.

446
00:21:01,239 --> 00:21:02,693
So there are other examples,

447
00:21:02,717 --> 00:21:04,3500000000001
I&amp;#39;m sure there are more to come.

448
00:21:05,66 --> 00:21:07,227
CA: But you&amp;#39;re not a visionary,

449
00:21:07,251 --> 00:21:09,204
and so it&amp;#39;s not up to you to name them.

450
00:21:09,228 --> 00:21:10,3870000000002
LT: No.

451
00:21:10,411 --> 00:21:11,459
(Laughter)

452
00:21:11,483 --> 00:21:13,447
It&amp;#39;s up to you guys to make them, right?

453
00:21:13,471 --> 00:21:14,734
CA: Exactly.

454
00:21:14,758 --> 00:21:15,916
Linus Torvalds,

455
00:21:15,94 --> 00:21:18,185
thank you for Linux,thank you for the Internet,

456
00:21:18,209 --> 00:21:20,074
thank you for all those Android phones.

457
00:21:20,098 --> 00:21:23,2949999999998
Thank you for coming here to TEDand revealing so much of yourself.

458
00:21:23,319 --> 00:21:24,471
LT: Thank you.

